    <fr:display-uri>008R</fr:display-uri>
    <fr:route>/lectures/008R/</fr:route>
    <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <html:p>        Here's another example: in intuitionistic logic, the argument from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p \land  q) \rightarrow  r]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p \rightarrow  r) \lor  (q \rightarrow  r)]]></fr:tex> fails.
        So it must have a counterexample.
        Here is one: let the model <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> be:
</html:p>
    <html:p>
      <fr:resource hash="ffd46402b0f460c1308e31e9fd96ff36">
        <fr:resource-content>
          <html:img src="/lectures/ffd46402b0f460c1308e31e9fd96ff36.svg" />
        </fr:resource-content>
        <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[\usepackage {tikz-cd}]]></fr:resource-source>
        <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[        \begin {tikzcd}
         & 4 : \{p, q, r\}\\
        2: \{p\} \arrow [ur] & & 3: \{q\} \arrow [ul]\\
        & 1: \{\} \arrow [ur] \arrow [ul] &\\
        \end {tikzcd}]]></fr:resource-source>
      </fr:resource>
    </html:p>
    <html:p>        Now, think about the values of the sentences in the argument at the point 1 in this model.
        We have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M((p \land  q) \rightarrow  r, 1) = Y]]></fr:tex>, since the only point reachable from 1 that assigns <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \land  q]]></fr:tex> in this model is 4, and 4 also assigns <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>.
        But both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \rightarrow  r]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q \rightarrow  r]]></fr:tex> get value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[?]]></fr:tex> at 1, for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \rightarrow  r]]></fr:tex> because of the presence of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2]]></fr:tex> in the model and for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q \rightarrow  r]]></fr:tex> because of the presence of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[3]]></fr:tex> in the model.
        So their disjunction also gets a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[?]]></fr:tex> at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex>.
        This gives the premise of this argument getting a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex> in this model, and the conclusion getting a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[?]]></fr:tex> there.
        So we have our counterexample.
</html:p>
    <html:p>        This model pictures a certain kind of dependency: if we have both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex>, then we must have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex> as well, but neither <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> nor <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex> on its own is enough for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>.
        This is a common kind of dependency: everything from light switches to the law includes situations where two things need to come together to suffice for something else, where neither one would suffice on its own.
        Our intuitionistic models can picture this very straightforwardly, as this example shows.
</html:p>
    <html:p>        However, <html:em>all</html:em> of the logics K3, LP, FDE, and classical logic validate this argument.
        So this seems to be one way in which intuitionistic implication is more flexible than the implications of all those logics.
</html:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
