            <fr:title text="Examples of intuitionistic counterexamples">Examples of intuitionistic counterexamples</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>29</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/008Q/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>008Q</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/008Q/</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>        You might recall that in intuitionistic logic, the argument <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  \neg  p \;/\; p]]></fr:tex> is not valid.
        So it must have a counterexample.
        Here is one:</html:p>
                <html:p>
                  <fr:resource hash="f1a7d0a3f6c04d5be23e616b23fbb414">
                    <fr:resource-content>
                      <html:img src="/lectures/f1a7d0a3f6c04d5be23e616b23fbb414.svg" />
                    </fr:resource-content>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[\usepackage {tikz-cd}]]></fr:resource-source>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[\begin {tikzcd}
         1: \{\} \arrow [r] & 2: \{p\}
        \end {tikzcd}]]></fr:resource-source>
                  </fr:resource>
                </html:p>
                <html:p>In this model, both points assign <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[?]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  p]]></fr:tex>; this is because each of them can reach some point that assigns <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>.
        (For both points, this reachable place is 2.)
</html:p>
                <html:p>        Because of this, in turn, both points assign <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  \neg  p]]></fr:tex>; neither of them can reach anywhere in the model that assigns <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  p]]></fr:tex>.
        So 1 assigns <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  \neg  p]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[?]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>; it is our counterexample, as it occurs in this model.
</html:p>
                <html:p>        Here's how you might interpret this: in intuitionistic logic, we might see <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  A]]></fr:tex> as saying something like "I know something that rules out my ever coming to know <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>".
        And we might know something that rules out our ever coming to know something that rules out our ever coming to know <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, without yet actually knowing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
                <html:p>        Looking at this model, we've got a situation at the point 1 where we don't yet know <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>, but there's no way in the model to ever come to know <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  p]]></fr:tex>.
        So we <html:em>do</html:em> know <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg \neg  p]]></fr:tex>.
        That means that the argument <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg \neg  p \;/\; p]]></fr:tex> can have a known premise and an unknown conclusion, so intuitionistic logic judges it invalid.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
